  {"q": "What is shadowing exactly?", "a": "Shadowing means listening to Japanese audio and repeating it simultaneously — not after, but at the same time. You mimic the speaker's rhythm, intonation, speed, and pitch in real-time, like a shadow following movement."},
  {"q": "How long should I shadow each day?", "a": "Start with 10-15 minutes daily. Even short sessions produce noticeable improvements in pronunciation within 2-3 weeks. Quality and focus matter more than duration — 10 focused minutes beats 30 distracted minutes."},
  {"q": "What materials should I use for shadowing?", "a": "Start with slow, clear audio like NHK Easy News or textbook dialogues. Progress to podcasts, drama scenes, and news broadcasts as your skill improves. Always choose material slightly below your comprehension level."},
  {"q": "Is shadowing better than repeating after the speaker?", "a": "Yes — research shows simultaneous repetition (shadowing) activates more brain pathways than delayed repetition. It forces real-time processing and develops automatic speech patterns rather than conscious translation."},
  {"q": "Can shadowing help with listening comprehension too?", "a": "Absolutely. Shadowing trains your brain to process Japanese at native speed. Many learners report significant listening improvement within 1-2 months of daily shadowing practice."}
];
const relatedTools = [{"name": "Kana Quiz", "url": "/japanese/tools/kana-quiz/"}, {"name": "Hiragana Chart", "url": "/japanese/tools/hiragana-chart/"}, {"name": "JLPT Vocabulary", "url": "/japanese/tools/jlpt-vocabulary/"}];
const headings = [
